\value{
A data.table with eight default columns:
\code{id} (user-provided row identifier), \code{subjid}, \code{param},
\code{agedays}, \code{sex}, \code{measurement}, \code{exclude} (exclusion
code or \code{"Include"}), and \code{bin_exclude} (\code{"Include"} or
\code{"Exclude"}).
\strong{Output fidelity:} the five echoed input columns (\code{subjid},
\code{param}, \code{agedays}, \code{sex}, \code{measurement}) carry the
user's \emph{verbatim submitted values} - gc never silently alters or drops
an input value. Reinterpretations needed to run the algorithm are
internal-only: imperial \code{param}/\code{measurement} are returned as
submitted (not converted to metric), \code{LENGTHCM} is returned as
\code{LENGTHCM} (not relabeled), a submitted \code{sex} code is returned as
submitted (gc's coerced \code{0}/\code{1}/\code{NA} is available as
\code{gc_sex} under \code{debug}/\code{full_detail}), and a submitted
\code{measurement} of \code{0} is returned as \code{0} (not \code{NaN}). A
value gc cannot use (uninterpretable \code{sex}; \code{0} or negative
\code{measurement}) is flagged \code{Exclude-Missing-Info} but still
returned as submitted.
If \code{tri_exclude = TRUE}, a \code{tri_exclude} column is also included
(\code{"Include"}, \code{"Same-Day"}, or \code{"Exclude"}).
If \code{cf_detail = TRUE}, \code{cf_status}, \code{cf_deltaz},
\code{cf_nextz}, \code{imperial}, \code{cf_dage_orig}, and
\code{cf_dage_next} columns are also included. \code{cf_status} labels every
row ("Orig", "CF-R", "CF-NR", "CF-E", or "Not-CF"); adult rows are
labeled "Adult" (no CF concept). For adult rows the three design-aid
columns (\code{imperial}, \code{cf_dage_orig}, \code{cf_dage_next}) are NA.
If \code{corr_detail = TRUE}, \code{corr_val} (per-value) and \code{corr_pt}
(per-subject) correction-status columns are also included
("Corrected"/"Uncorrected"/"Adult").
If \code{recenter_detail = TRUE}, the recentered CSD z-score columns
\code{tbc.sd}, \code{ctbc.sd}, and \code{rcmedian.sd} are also included
(child rows only; NA for adult rows) as a stable output contract.
If \code{debug = TRUE}, intermediate z-score diagnostic columns
(\code{sd.orig}, \code{sd.corr}, \code{tbc.sd}, \code{ctbc.sd}) plus the
perturbation z-scores (\code{tbc.p_plus},
\code{tbc.p_minus}, \code{ctbc.p_plus}, \code{ctbc.p_minus}) are retained
for child rows (NA for adult rows), plus \code{gc_sex} (gc's interpreted
integer sex, \code{0}/\code{1}/\code{NA}, used by the algorithm; the
verbatim submission stays in \code{sex}).
If \code{full_detail = TRUE}, all of the above optional columns are included.
Unless \code{unit_error_range = FALSE}, a \code{unit_error_range} logical
column is also included (on by default; informational, never an exclusion).

\strong{Column naming:} The six data columns (\code{id}, \code{subjid},
\code{param}, \code{agedays}, \code{sex}, \code{measurement}) are renamed
to match the user's original argument expressions when those can be
resolved to a simple name.
For example, \code{cleangrowth(subjid = dt\$patid, ...)} returns a column
named \code{patid}. Simple bare-name references (e.g., \code{subjid =
  patient_vec}) are also preserved. Complex expressions (e.g., function
calls, literals) fall back to the canonical name.

The full catalog of exclusion codes (child and adult, covering both the
Summary \code{exclude} values and the step-level \code{exclude_detailed}
values) is documented in \code{vignette("exclusion-codes")}.
}
\description{
Two calling styles are supported:
}
\details{
\enumerate{
\item \strong{Data-frame style (recommended).} Pass a single data.frame
or data.table as \code{data}. The \code{subjid}, \code{param},
\code{agedays}, \code{sex}, \code{measurement}, and \code{id}
arguments are then column-name strings identifying which columns in
\code{data} to use. Each defaults to the canonical name (e.g.
\code{"subjid"}), so if your columns already use those names you can
just call \code{cleangrowth(data = my_df)}. Use the column-name
arguments only to remap (e.g. \code{subjid = "patid"}).
\item \strong{Vector style (legacy).} Omit \code{data} and pass each
of \code{subjid}, \code{param}, \code{agedays}, \code{sex}, and
\code{measurement} as a vector. Retained for backward compatibility
with existing code; new code should use the data-frame style.
}

All vectors (or the columns referenced in \code{data}) must have the
same length and be aligned row-for-row. Pulling values from different
datasets is not supported and not checked for.
}
\examples{
\donttest{
# Data-frame style (recommended): canonical column names, just pass the
# data.frame. Add an `id` column for best results.
df_stats <- as.data.frame(syngrowth)
df_stats <- df_stats[df_stats$subjid \%in\% unique(df_stats[, "subjid"])[1:5], ]
df_stats$id <- seq_len(nrow(df_stats))
clean_stats <- cleangrowth(data = df_stats)

# Data-frame style with remapped column names
my_df <- df_stats
names(my_df)[names(my_df) == "subjid"] <- "patid"
clean_stats <- cleangrowth(data = my_df, subjid = "patid")

# Vector style (legacy)
clean_stats <- cleangrowth(subjid = df_stats$subjid,
                           param = df_stats$param,
                           agedays = df_stats$agedays,
                           sex = df_stats$sex,
                           measurement = df_stats$measurement,
                           id = df_stats$id)

# Parallel processing: run using 2 cores and batches
clean_stats <- cleangrowth(data = df_stats,
                           parallel = TRUE,
                           num.batches = 2)
}
}
